al. Its five thematic chapters lead to a conclusion that, on balance, emigration determined the churches' fates to a far greater extent than the churches determined emigrants' fates.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSocial sciences. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Ireland.2bisacsh  aChristianity.  aIrish monks.  achurches.  aclergy.  aclerical advice-giving.  aemigrant welfare.  afaith.  amass emigration.  anineteenth-century Ireland.  aparish clergymen.  areligious change.1 aRoddy, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2014 eBook-Packagez978311128357940uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526147226zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526147226zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526147226/original  a978-3-11-128357-9 Manchester University Press 2014 eBook-Packageb2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA